{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506129"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2518"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2518"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.17,0.06,0.44,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54042"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2518"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41932"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54042"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with the intention of reducing her alcohol consumption. Over the last 12 months, her alcohol consumption has increased from a binge pattern on weekends (approximately eight standard drinks) to one bottle of red wine a day. She was admitted to hospital one week ago to facilitate alcohol withdrawal and has not had a drink since she was admitted. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She reports no cravings for alcohol since discharge. She has since moved back home with her parents for support. She notes that one of her current concerns is that there are a number of unavoidable work events over the next month where alcohol will be present - she would like to be able to have one drink at these if possible. Arrangements are made to provide her with a comprehensive therapy package, which will include social work input, counselling and case management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents is most likely to be of benefit with regards to her alcohol dependence?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acamprosate","Disulfiram","Diazepam","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate agent for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003ENaltrexone\u003C/strong\u003E. Naltrexone aids in alcohol cessation by acting as a \u03bc-opioid antagonist, reducing the reinforcing euphoric reward of alcohol. It supports abstinence and reduces the severity of relapse. Naltrexone is particularly useful in this patient, as it also helps reduce heavy drinking in people who continue drinking during treatment, thereby reducing her risk for heavy drinking at work events if she chooses to have a drink there.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcamprosate\u003C/strong\u003E is a structural analogue of GABA, which is thought to decrease positive reinforcement of alcohol intake and withdrawal cravings. While acamprosate is considered first-line in patients with alcohol dependence seeking to maintain abstinence, it is not as appropriate to prescribe in this patient as complete abstinence (i.e., avoiding one or two drinks at a work function) may be difficult for her.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisulfiram\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer considered first-line treatment due to difficulties with compliance and toxicity. Disulfiram is an acetaldehyde dehydrogenase inhibitor, which produces a toxic \u0027hangover\u0027 effect for patients who drink alcohol. This would not be suitable for a patient who may have occasional drinks at work events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in acute alcohol withdrawal, but has no evidence for assisting in alcohol cessation and preventing relapse. As this patient has already completed withdrawal, diazepam would not be appropriate for her current situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid antagonist used in opioid toxicity and is not to be confused with naltrexone. It has no role in the management of alcohol dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to pharmacological treatment, the comprehensive therapy package including social work input, counselling, and case management is crucial for this patient\u0027s recovery. This multidisciplinary approach, combined with naltrexone, offers the best chance of success in managing her alcohol dependence while allowing for the possibility of controlled drinking at unavoidable social events.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Naltrexone supports abstinence from alcohol and reduces severity of relapse, but also helps reduce heavy drinking in those who continue drinking during treatment.","Naltrexone is particularly useful for patients who may have difficulty maintaining complete abstinence in social situations."],"references":["Crowley P. Long-term drug treatment of patients with alcohol dependence. Aust Prescr. 2015 Apr;38(2):41-3. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4653998/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2518"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T10:15:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-30T07:37:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54042"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":nu